<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Mexico leads Latam plunge as
Dow climbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
The US market showed potential for a year-end rally yesterday as equity
prices climbed above 3,800 on the Dow indicator for the first time since
November 18, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped more than 50 points during the day
before falling back to close 34.65 up at 3,801.80. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 rose 2.51 to 459.61, the American Stock Exchange
composite increased by 2.63 to 427.93 and the Nasdaq composite gained 8.61
at 737.12. Trading volume on the New York SE amounted to 380.5m shares.
With yesterday's gains, the Dow has now made up most of the ground lost by a
sharp sell-off in late-November. On November 22 the Dow plunged 91 points
amid investor fears that the Federal Reserve, which had raised interest
rates on November 15, would boost rates again in December.
Many on Wall Street had come to believe that there would be no traditional
year-end uptick because of all the insecurity about interest rates. With
chances of another rate increase this year low, investors yesterday were
watching to see if the day's advance could turn into a full-blown rally.
Cyclical stocks jumped with the market, the Morgan Stanley cyclical index
adding 1.4 per cent. Mead rose Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 49 1/4 and Tenneco
Dollars 1 to Dollars 43 1/8 .
ADRs of Mexican companies dropped in the wake of Tuesday's devaluation of
the peso, which caused a sharp fall in Mexico's bolsa. Bellwether stock
Telefonos de Mexico lost Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 45 and Grupo Tribasa fell
Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 22 3/8 .
Elsewhere, Biogen forged ahead Dollars 6 5/8 or 18.6 per cent to Dollars 42
1/4 on rumours that the biotech company may be the subject of a takeover
bid. Cigna tumbled Dollars 4 7/8 or 7.3 per cent to Dollars 61 7/8 after AM
Best lowered the insurance company's credit rating.
Aluminum Company of America put on Dollars 2 at Dollars 82 3/4 after the
company said it expected a gain of about Dollars 295m for the fourth quarter
of this year after a loss of nearly Dollars 87m for the last quarter of
1993.
Intel, up Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 62 5/8 , continued to gain from its
announcement that it would replace flawed Pentium chips on demand. The
shares had been under pressure because of negative publicity surrounding the
chip's flaw. Shares in computer makers that use the Pentium chip were mixed.
Canada
Toronto enjoyed a third day of solid gains, but the upward trend stirred
fears that the market was reaching its short term high.
The TSE 300 composite index added 21.49 at 4,175.62, while turnover was the
fourth heaviest on record, reaching 97m shares valued at CDollars 921m.
Rises led falls by 460 to 369.
Mexico
Mexican stocks went into freefall as investors were taken by surprise by the
255 basis-point rise in local interest rates to 16 per cent. However, the
market ended well above the day's worst on bargain hunting with a decline of
3.1 per cent on the IPC index, having initially plunged 11.7 per cent. The
IPC lost a net 70.50 at 2,203.67. Volume totalled a fairly heavy 119.4m
shares.
The rate move followed a 15 per cent devaluation of the peso on Tuesday,
which had been triggered by the outflow of capital, particularly from US and
European investors, as a result of violence in the southern state of
Chiapas.
Investors were now worried that the government might be forced to make a
second devaluation, commented analysts in London.
However, Mr Nigel Rendell, emerging markets strategist at James Capel,
remained positive on the market, assuming there was no further devaluation.
He argued that while the initial consequences of devaluation for some
companies would be negative, over a longer time period the negatives should
be outweighed by positives, namely export growth and, hopefully, lower
interest rates; while companies with substantial dollar earnings should
outperform.
Mr Roger Palmer, director of emerging markets at Kleinwort Benson, took a
similar line, and suspected that the market was going through a storm which
would gradually subside. He now saw company earnings growth between 30 to 40
per cent in 1995.
Brazil
Shares in Sao Paulo plummeted 6.4 per cent in reaction to the news from
Mexico. The Bovespa index closed 3,038 off at 44,952. Volume was RDollars
364m.
A broker said the mood on Brazil's markets suffered further yesterday from
rumours that two large and reputable brokerage houses could be close to
collapse.
Argentina
In Buenos Aires the Merval index finished 29.65 or 5.7 per cent down at
486.70 on worries about the fallout from Tuesday's devaluation of the peso.
Volumes increased amid the sell-off. Turnover on the open outcry market
totalled a strong 41.3m pesos.
