</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): US revival underpins bourse
recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The absence of a US interest rate rise, even with a subsequent fall in the
Dow overnight, seemed to lay the foundations of yesterday's bourse recovery,
writes Our Markets Staff. In the afternoon, Wall Street's revival took the
process further.
FRANKFURT looked tentative on the session with a Dax index rise of 6.73 to
2,086.66; but at the end of the afternoon the Ibis-indicated Dax was 15.34
higher at 2,095.50.
Turnover eased from DM4.5bn to DM4.4bn. Chemicals led shares upward, Bayer
ending the afternoon DM8 higher at DM361.50, and Hoechst rising even faster
with a gain of DM8.40 to DM828. There was talk of small fund buying of the
sector and, late in the day, of Hoechst's planned price rises for technical
fibres.
Mr Shaw Bridges, European chemicals specialist at Merrill Lynch in London,
said that the industry had seen good increases in physical sales volume, and
was now moving into a period of better pricing. Hoechst had experienced
disappointing profit margins for a long time; it had also been relatively
late in restructuring its operations, with the cost-cutting that this
entailed, but analysts now seemed to believe that the process was well under
way.
PARIS caught the tail of Wall Street's opening rally and the CAC-40 index
accelerated 16.17 to 1,940.89.
Smith New Court put a buy note out on Valeo, up FFr8.50 at FFr248.50, and
made a case for the car components manufacturer's being the target of a
takeover bid. It argued that:
the company was relatively small;
its major shareholder, the holding company, Cerus, remained in bad financial
shape and 'would not be in a position to defend Valeo if a raider attacked';
the company would be net cash positive by the end of next year, and by 1996
the cash pile could amount to more than FFr3bn. 'Clearly, the cash could be
attractive to a raider,' added the broker.
Bollore Technologies, the diversified industrial group, added FFr7.80 to
FFr447.00 as it confirmed reports that it was negotiating the sale of 11
ships for around FFr800m. If successful, the sale would cut the group's debt
to some FFr4bn.
MILAN stood aloof from the drama unfolding in parliament and the market
continued to rally for a sixth consecutive day, with the weak lira again
providing the catalyst for foreign equity investors. The Comit index rose
11.15 or 1.8 per cent to L624.06 on the view that, one way or another, the
government of Mr Silvio Berlusconi was about to fall.
The index has bounced by 7.4 per cent from its year's low on December 13.
Foreign investors have been attracted by expectations that the government
would be replaced by a so-called institutional government, headed by a
non-partisan prime minister from outside parliament, which would quickly
bring an end to the political uncertainty.
Mr John Stewart at InterEuropa in Milan, warned, however that foreign
markets were probably over-optimistic about how quickly an institutional
government might be formed. He added that domestic investors thought that
fresh elections were more likely.
Among blue chips, Fiat rose L125 or 2.1 per cent to L5,974 as the company
reiterated that it had recorded 'an extraordinary turnaround' in 1994.
Stet rose L123 to L4,563 after announcing that consolidated net profit for
1994 would be around L2,000bn, up from L1,530bn last year.
ZURICH saw the SMI index 21.4 higher at 2,636.1 in relatively active
trading. Roche certificates extended Tuesday's solid gain, closing SFr110
higher at SFr6,300, benefiting from the relatively strong dollar.
Among second liners, Ems-Chemie rose SFr100 to SFr3,930 as SBC issued
warrants on the share.
MADRID's equity market mirrored weakness in the peseta and in domestic
bonds, shaken by a further high level arrest in connection with vigilante
attacks on the Basque separatist group, Eta. The general index fell another
1.87 to 291.59, threatening the 1994 low of 288.65.
Some relief from the gloom came from the planned introduction to the Ibex-35
index of leading stocks, from January 2, of the paper group, Empresa
Nacional de Celulosa (Ence), and the fashion retailer, Cortefiel, whose
shares rose Pta30 to Pta3,195 and Pta40 to Pta3,995 respectively. But the
departing stocks, Aguas de Barcelona and the builder, Huarte, fell by more
than the newcomers rose, with drops of Pta75 to Pta2,465 and Pta30 to
Pta1,330.
AMSTERDAM moved firmly ahead although trading activity remained relatively
muted. The AEX index added 2.71 to 413.35, just below its session best.
VNU, up Fl 2.70 at Fl 178.80, announced after the close of business that it
was acquiring a UK information company, Calyx.
Among the multinationals there was a gain of Fl 3.30 in Unilever to Fl
202.20 as investors applauded its recent reorganisation announcement.
Written and edited by William Cochrane, John Pitt and Michael Morgan
