<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / International Company News: TCI takes stake in Microsoft
on-line venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Tele-Communications Inc, the leading US cable television service provider,
has acquired a stake in The Microsoft Network, a computer on-line service
that Microsoft, the world's largest software company, plans to launch next
year.
For Dollars 125m in TCI stock, the cable group has acquired a 20 per cent
stake in the newly formed Microsoft Online Services Partnership, a general
partnership formed to develop and market Microsoft's on-line services.
Microsoft currently holds the remaining 80 per cent.
The partnership between Microsoft and TCI reflects the convergence of
computer, communications and entertainment technologies which is expected to
result in broadband on-line services within the next few years.
Such services, delivered via high-speed communications lines, will be
capable of offering interactive multimedia information, including video and
sophisticated graphics. This is in contrast to today's on-line services,
which are largely limited to text and simple graphics.
'As we build our broadband networks, this partnership will give us the
ability to offer the Microsoft Network as a high-speed, interactive on-line
service,' said Mr Bruce Ravenel, senior vice-president of TCI Technology
Ventures, a division of TCI.
Microsoft said the development of 'cable modems' - devices that link a
personal computer to a TV cable network - would lift demand for on-line
services and enable information providers such as news organisations and
other publishers to gradually migrate their on-line service offerings to
more sophisticated broadband services.
</TEXT>
