<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / International Company News: TWA proposes new restructuring
plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Trans World Airlines, the US airline trying to avert a cash crisis,
yesterday said it had a new plan for a financial restructuring which it
believed would prove acceptable to its creditors.
TWA also said it had Dollars 107m in cash at the end of November. This was
slightly down from the Dollars 114m it had at the end of September, but the
airline said the figure was rising.
TWA, once one of the world's best-known airlines, went into Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection in 1992.
It re-emerged in November last year, with creditors holding 55 per cent of
the equity and employees holding 45 per cent. It has not made a profit
since.
Last October the airline announced a rescue plan under which it would nearly
halve its debt by asking creditors to swap Dollars 800m worth of loans for
equity.
As a result, the creditors' stake would rise to possibly 70 per cent and the
employees' stake would fall to about 30 per cent. Some creditors opposed the
plan because they wanted a better deal.
TWA has now come up with a revised proposal under which creditors will trade
less debt for the same amount of equity.
Mr Jeffrey Erickson, chief executive, said that although further talks could
not be ruled out, he was optimistic that the plan would be approved.
</TEXT>
