<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / International Company News: Aramco negotiates Greek oil
stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE and ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Greece's Vardinoyannis group is negotiating the sale of up to 50 per cent of
Motoroil Hellas, its oil refining company, to Aramco, the Saudi Arabian
state oil company. It would be the largest foreign investment in Greece for
several decades.
It would also be Aramco's first investment in Europe, although private Saudi
interests earlier this year took over Sweden's OK Petroleum group, the
Nordic region's largest refiner.
Motoroil, owned by two Panama-registered companies which belong to members
of the Vardinoyannis family, controls Greece's largest private refinery with
capacity of 4.5m tonnes annually.
The Motoroil refinery near Corinth in southern Greece supplies a chain of
600 petrol stations around Greece controlled by the Vardinoyannis group and
exports oil products through a separate trading company. Analysts in Athens
said the refinery, which was modernised five years ago, is valued at over
Dollars 400m.
Aramco has long been seeking a European refining and marketing outlet. Such
a development would be in line with a trend among many state oil companies
to develop downstream networks in their main crude oil markets.
Kuwait Petroleum Corporation, for example, has built an extensive European
refining and marketing network under the Q8 brand.
Aramco is a partner in the Star downstream joint venture with Texaco in the
US. It recently acquired a 40 per cent stake in Petron Corporation, the
leading oil company in the Philippines.
Previous Aramco overtures to European refiners have generally foundered over
failure to agree a price. Aramco's European ambitions have, however, been
pared back recently. This is because of the maturity of the European market,
a shortage of investment funds due to relatively low crude oil prices and a
shift in strategic emphasis to Asia, the world's fastest-growing oil market.
Analysts say Dollars 400m would be a good price for the refinery. The
location would give the Saudis a European base relatively close to home and
well positioned to supply new markets in eastern Europe.
Motoroil posted profits last year of Dr6bn (Dollars 25m) on turnover of
Dr189.2bn.
The Vardinoyannis group operates one of Greece's largest tanker fleets, but
has diversified into banking and services since 1990.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Vardinoyannis.
    Motoroil Hellas.
    Saudi Aramco.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GRZ  Greece, EC.
    SAZ  Saudi Arabia, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2911 Petroleum Refining.
    P6719 Holding Companies, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
