<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / International Company News: Swedbank takes 7.5% stake in
Finnish bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Swedbank, the Nordic region's biggest bank by asset value, yesterday made
its first move to take a stake in a foreign bank, buying a 7.5 per cent
stake in Finland's Aktia Bank for SKr47m (Dollars 6.25m).
The Swedish bank is to take up 1.5m of 2.5m new shares being issued at a
price of FM20 a share by Aktia, a small bank with assets of FM8.6bn. Aktia
intends to apply for a listing on the Helsinki stock exchange next year.
Aktia's main market is in Finland's small Swedish-speaking minority.
Swedbank, with assets of almost SKr490bn, has become a force in Sweden. It
emerged in its present form when a group of Swedish savings banks were
thrown together in 1992 following the loan loss crisis which hit Sweden's
banks.
It has become profitable this year and plans a listing on the Stockholm
stock exchange in 1995.
However, the bank said its Aktia acquisition did not signal any strategic
diversification overseas.
</TEXT>
