<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Boddington purchases nursing homes from
Bupa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Boddington Group is to expand its nursing homes division by about 60 per
cent with the purchase of the Care for the Elderly subsidiary of Bupa, the
UK's largest private healthcare provider, for up to Pounds 30.7m.
The subsidiary has 448 beds in 10 homes mainly in southern England. It made
pre-tax profits of Pounds 1.8m on turnover of Pounds 8.6m in 1993.
The deal will make Boddington the leader in the premium sector of the
nursing homes market with a 'powerful position' in south-east England.
The price was criticised as too high by Laing and Buisson, a care home
consultant. A typical valuation for homes was Pounds 40,000 per bed but
Boddington was paying over Pounds 60,000, it said.
Boddington said the price compared favourably with, for example, the sum it
paid recently to build a home in Hertfordshire. Moreover, it was buying
freehold properties valued at about Pounds 23m.
</TEXT>
