FT  22 DEC 94 / UK Company News: Tate &amp; Lyle plans Staley expansion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tate &amp; Lyle, the sugars and sweeteners group, yesterday announced a Dollars
78m (Pounds 50m) expansion project at AE Staley, its maize wet milling
subsidiary in the US.
As part of the project, due to be completed by June next year, Staley's
Lafayette South plant will be expanded at a cost of Dollars 45m (Pounds
28.9m) to produce additional high fructose corn syrup. This is the first
phase of an expansion which will eventually more than double capacity at the
plant.
Meanwhile, the Lafayette North (Sagamore) plant will be expanded at a cost
of Dollars 33m (Pounds 21.1m), doubling the modified starch capacity.
At the same time Staley will complete the Dollars 20m (Pounds 12.8m)
modernisation of its starch processing facility at Decatur, Illinois.
The expenditure forms part of Tate's planned Pounds 175m capital investment
programme for the year to September 1995.
