<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Names win in court as Lloyd's unveils fall in capacity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hard-hit Lloyd's of London members notched up another court victory
yesterday - theoretically worth Pounds 80m - as the insurance market
unveiled figures showing still more Names ceasing active participation and a
fall in underwriting capacity.
The High Court ruling on damages for Names on the Gooda Walker syndicate
387, which reported some of the biggest losses in Lloyd's history, coincided
with figures showing the market's underwriting capacity will fall to Pounds
10.2bn in 1995 compared with Pounds 10.9bn this year.
The number of Names - individuals whose assets have traditionally supported
the insurance market - actively underwriting will fall by about 15 per cent
to 14,804, the biggest percentage fall for three years.
However, Mr David Rowland, Lloyd's chairman, said this was in line with the
market's requirements. 'Lloyd's underwriters are still being selective in
the business that they write. Present market conditions indicate that there
are good opportunities for underwriting profitable business in 1995,' he
said.
Much of the shortfall in capacity resulting from Names seeking to resign has
been made up by new corporate capital, which will account for about 23 per
cent of capacity next year, compared with 15 per cent in 1994.
New corporate investors raised Pounds 331m for investing in 1995, largely in
'dedicated' companies which invest in only a few syndicates and are regarded
as embryonic insurance companies.
Lloyd's leaders hope corporate capital will provide a long-term source of
capacity, and forecast that the number of traditional Names may fall to a
few thousand over the next few years. But fears about outstanding
liabilities and litigation, which may make it hard for the market to pass
regulators' solvency tests, has put off many investors this year.
Many Names are expected to convert from trading on the basis of unlimited
liability to limited liability, though only four have done this in time for
1995. Another 19 people are entering as traditional Lloyd's Names.
The Gooda Walker 387 judgment puts the approximately 300 Names who brought
the case at the head of the queue of those seeking to tap the pool of
'errors and omissions' insurance cover available for negligence awards.
Separately, the Court of Appeal yesterday overturned an earlier court
decision which had barred about 1,000 Names suing for losses incurred on
Merrett insurance syndicates because they did not lodge the claim in time.
US places bulk of new Lloyd's capital for 1995, Page 9
See Lex
</TEXT>
<XX>
