<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sift through the nonsense on screen as the holiday looms and you can find
the odd serious offering. First Sight (7.30pm BBC2) is a timely look at the
drinks trade - from the other side of the law. Booze-running is big
business, as America found out during Prohibition; though our
Channel-leaping trippers loading up with the product of grape, grain and hop
have yet to resort to shoot-outs with the customs officers we see going
about their eagle-eyed calling.
More divided sympathies, more trouble in store awaiting the day of reckoning
in Channel 4's Witness (9pm). Morehouse College, Atlanta, teaches its black
students to be proud, confident and ruthless. When these qualities are
allied to extremism - any sort of religious fundamentalism or political
militancy - it all starts to look alarming. The irony is that the place
turns out the rigidly conservative mindset one associates with the wearers
of white sheets rather than black skin - yet it produced Martin Luther King
and the film director Spike Lee. A disturbing film.
</TEXT>
