<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Coopers' Maxwell move fails
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Coopers and Lybrand, the leading accountancy firm, has failed in its attempt
to stop an investigation into its auditing of the Maxwell Group pension
funds, Jim Kelly writes.
The Joint Disciplinary Scheme, the accountancy profession's regulator,
wanted to investigate its role as an auditor.
High Court judges Lord Justice Henry and Mr Justice Kay said: 'The question
should be addressed promptly, and its resolution should not await and be
dependent on the final resolution of civil proceedings, which may be some
years off.'
The case hinged on whether regulators can investigate cases still being
heard in criminal and civil courts. As such it is seen as a test case for
regulators in all sectors, including the financial markets.
Coopers and Lybrand argued that if it were to lose a case before the JDS the
result could be 'catastrophic' for the firm.
The accountancy firm Price Waterhouse had previously successfully argued
that a JDS investigation into its part in the BCCI affair should await the
conclusion of civil actions.
Coopers said: 'The decision has gone against us. We are taking legal advice
at the moment.' An appeal is seen as extremely likely.
</TEXT>
