<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Base rate rise indicated at Clarke talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This month's rise in UK bank base rates was foreshadowed in November's
discussions on monetary policy between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
and Mr Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England, according to
minutes of their meeting released yesterday.
The minutes show Mr George saying there was a case, if evidence on prices
and activity was taken at face value, for a rise in interest rates at the
time of the meeting on November 2.
The governor said that on the basis of what was currently known, rates would
'probably need to rise before very long'.
He was, however, 'inclined to wait a little' to see whether clearer signs
appeared of an easing in the rate of UK growth and how wage and price
pressures devel-oped.
Mr Clarke said Britain was having a healthy and well-balanced recovery with
inflation remaining low. But further ahead the data were 'somewhat mixed'.
His inclination was not to change rates at the November meeting and in his
view the evidence at that time showed no need to act. 'Looking ahead, we
would need to remain cautious and alert to the potential risks,' he said.
In concluding there was agreement to leave rates unchanged, Mr Clarke noted
that there was uncertainty about the effect that the tax rises already
announced before last month's Budget might have on consumer demand.
He said it was important to check that statistics which had a good record as
indicators of inflation in the past were still reliable.
Although the minutes reveal the now familiar nuances indicating the
difference in approach to rates between governor and chancellor, they bear
out both men's claims that the December 7 base rate increase to 6.25 per
cent from 5.75 per cent was based on economic and not political factors.
</TEXT>
