<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Business rates blow for London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies in London will pay more than expected in business rates next year,
making them unwilling to accept higher rents and more likely to move to new
premises, property experts said yesterday.
While property values in central London have fallen by up to 60 per cent
since business rates were last set in 1988, transitional arrangements
outlined in last month's Budget limit cuts in rates bills to 5 per cent a
year for large buildings.
The average central London office occupier currently pays business rates of
about Pounds 16 a sq ft. Based on property values that liability should have
fallen to about Pounds 6.75 a sq ft.
Under the transitional arrangements, however, occupiers will still be paying
Pounds 15.55 a sq ft next year - a saving of only 45p.
Property agents said higher than expected rates would make it more difficult
for landlords to charge higher rents.
Jones Lang Wootton, the surveyors, has reduced its rental growth forecasts
for top City properties in the next two years, although it expects the
transitional arrangements to be more generous to central London occupiers
thereafter.
Rates on new buildings - occupied for the first time after April 1995 - will
be set immediately at the lower level, reflecting the current value of the
premises.
This will make new offices up to Pounds 10 a sq ft cheaper to occupy than
older premises and could encourage developers to press ahead with new
buildings.
Yet agents said that business rates would not in themselves spark a
development boom.
Sir Brian Goswell, of Healy &amp; Baker, the surveyors, said: 'What really
matters to a developer is whether he can find a tenant for a new building.
Most tenants are locked into old leases and do not have the option of
moving.'
</TEXT>
