<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Obituary of Sir Henry Phelps Brown: Rare master of economics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'It has long been claimed that an economist is not trained who is not
numerate; but neither is he trained if he is not historiate.' This argument,
made in Sir Henry Phelps Brown's presidential address to the Royal Economic
Society, published in the Economic Journal in 1972, defined his creed as an
economist.
In his outstanding work on labour economics Phelps Brown combined economics
with history, sociology and statistics. This eclecticism made him somewhat
unfashionable. He returned the compliment in complaining of modern
theoretical economics that 'its usefulness is not equal to its distinction'.
Born in Calne, Wiltshire, on February 10 1906, Phelps Brown was educated at
Taunton School and Wadham College, Oxford, where he was secretary of the
Oxford Union in 1928 and gained first class honours in modern history in
1927, and politics, philosophy and economics in 1929. He was a fellow of New
College from 1930 to 1947. In 1936 he published The Framework of the Pricing
System, which contained an orthodox exposition of marginal theory.
After distinguished war service, Phelps Brown became the first professor of
the economics of labour at the University of London, teaching at the London
School of Economics until 1968. A Course in Applied Economics was first
published in 1951 and issued in a second edition with Jack Wiseman in 1964.
Economics of Labour appeared in 1962.
Among the principal concerns and, indeed, tensions in Phelps Brown's work
was the relative role of market pressures and historical forces in pay
determination. In 1968 he published A Century of Pay, analysing pay and
production in France, Germany, Sweden, the UK and US. Among its conclusions
were that 'the number of jobs increased at the same rate, decade by decade .
. . as the number of applicants' and that 'wages, in terms of the product,
rose in the same proportion as productivity'. In similar vein, he published
The Inequality of Pay in 1977, which argued that market forces were more
important than 'custom, convention, status, or power'.
LSE statistical studies were republished, in 1981, in Phelps Brown and
Sheila V. Hopkin's, A Perspective on Wages and Prices. This included an
analysis of real wages in building, first published in 1955, which was based
on a wage series and a widely used and justly celebrated consumer price
index, going back seven centuries. The principal finding was one of
remarkable stability in real wages, with no sustained change in 500 out of
the 690 years. Similar stability was found in wage differentials between
craftsmen and labourers, this being ascribed to the 'inertia of convention'.
Alongside such predominantly statistical studies went analyses of the
history of British labour relations. One such was The Growth of British
Industrial Relations: a study from the standpoint of 1906-14, published in
1959. Another was The Origins of Trade Union Power, published in 1983.
In the latter, he argued: 'Much of the history of trade unionism can be
written out of (the) clash between the requirements that the economic system
imposes impersonally on labour as a factor of production, and the welfare of
workers as human beings, seeking a livelihood from the exercise of
particular skills, and attached to particular neighbourhoods.' Sympathetic
to incomes policy, he concluded that the threat to it 'arises when the trade
unions have not too much power but too little'. He suggested unions should
be made jointly responsible for decisions.
Phelps Brown thought that attitudes 'are among the basic determinants of
history'. His own determined his approach not just to his work, but to
economics as a subject. Economists, he suggested in 'The radical reflections
of an applied economist,' published in the Banca Nazionale del Lavoro
Quarterly Review in 1980, should not merely 'study economics as that subject
now stands' but try 'to gain an understanding of the economic aspects of
human affairs so as to be able to contribute to their healthier
development'.
An element in that contribution was work on public bodies. Phelps Brown
served on the Council on Prices, Productivity and Income in 1959; on the
National Economic Development Council in 1962; on the OECD Working Party on
Wages and Labour Mobility from 1963 to 1964; and on the Royal Commission on
the Distribution of Income and Wealth from 1974 to 1978. His interest in the
commission led to a monumental last work, Egalitarianism and the Generation
of Inequality, published in 1988.
Phelps Brown was president of the Royal Economic Society from 1970 to 1972.
In his presidential address he said: 'In an experimental science,
assumptions chosen a priori can be tested against facts of observation; but
in economics there is little opportunity for experiment.' Furthermore,
'though fortunately some possibilities do exist of testing assumptions about
behaviour against statistical aggregates, running regressions against time
series is only likely to deceive'.
If assumptions cannot be tested, their plausibility can only be assessed
from observation and analysis. For this reason, he said, 'we ought to value
powers of observation more highly than powers of abstraction, and the
insight of the historian more than the rigour of the mathematicians'.
One reason this approach to economics has become rare is that, as he noted
in his 1980 article for the Banca Nazionale del Lavoro: 'The more abstract
the material, the more evident is the intellectual power of those who master
it. For this among other reasons the economic theorist moves among his
fellows with a certain majesty.' He also admitted that historical analysis
may explain, but cannot yield predictions. Among the most important reasons,
however, is that what Phelps Brown wanted economists to do is so difficult.
He, however, was a master of the art.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
</TP>
<XX>
People:-
</XX>
<PE>Sir Henry Phelps Brown.
</PE>
