<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Hurd brokers cabinet referendum deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior ministers believe the cabinet is moving towards a consensus on Mr
John Major's commitment to hold a referendum on further European integration
only if significant constitutional issues are at stake.
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, is understood to have established broad
backing for the prime minister's formula - set out in a Financial Times
interview on Tuesday - after contacting the entire cabinet.
The emerging consensus reflects increasing confidence among ministers that
the European Union's 1996 intergovernmental conference is unlikely to
produce the drama of the last conference at Maastricht in 1991.
There is also agreement that there is no need for a firm commitment to hold
a referendum on the prospect of a single European currency because a
decision to go ahead is unlikely before 1999.
Mr Major's formula stops short of committing the government to a referendum
 -meeting the concerns of pro-European cabinet ministers, led by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, chancellor, and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
It also has the support of leading Eurosceptics such as Mr John Redwood,
Welsh secretary, who fear a firm commitment would reduce the pressure on Mr
Major to veto any unexpected proposals for constitutional change at the 1996
conference.
The Eurosceptics believe an undertaking to hold a referendum on a single
currency would be counter-productive because it would increase the chances
of a decision to go ahead.
The broad support for Mr Major's approach to the referendum issue makes it
unlikely that he will decide to offer a clearer commitment to a referendum
on either the intergovernmental conference issue or the single currency in
the new year, as has been widely suggested.
The prime minister may, however, restate his approach more clearly, probably
linking the role of referendums on European questions to the constitutional
implications of Labour's plans to reform the House of Lords and set up
Scottish and Welsh parliaments.
The cabinet's defence and overseas policy committee, chaired by Mr Major,
will start preparing a detailed case early next year calling on the 1996
meeting to limit itself to changes to improve the Maastricht treaty.
Mr Hurd is expected to take the lead in staking out an approach to the
conference negotiations on which the broad mass of the Conservative
parliamentary party can stand.
Mr Michael Howard, the moderately Eurosceptic home secretary, is seen as a
central figure in crafting an approach acceptable to all but the most
extreme Tory critics of the EU.
Senior ministers loyal to Mr Major are dismissive of the nine backbenchers
who lost or gave up the Conservative whip last month after a rebellion
against higher UK contributions to the union. There is concern, however,
about the mood of party workers.
</TEXT>
