<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / SIB sets guidelines for probe on pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Life companies which seem to have advised the most people to leave
employers' pensions schemes and take out personal plans will have to make
greater efforts to identify potential victims than other insurers, City
regulators said yesterday.
The Securities and Investments Board, the chief financial services watchdog,
said companies which could show that they had fewer victims in the
categories of investors most at risk would not have to go to such lengths to
persuade them to respond.
The differences in how far life insurers will have to go were revealed as
SIB published guidance about how the millions of personal pension holders
should be approached to identify those who should be compensated.
The guidance contains three warnings that the exercise must not be used to
try to sell new policies to investors.
The format of covering letters and the questionnaire to go to personal
pension holders have been prescribed by SIB after research intended to make
them understandable.
The questionnaire is an important step in identifying the estimated 850,000
people who were advised to take a personal pension and opt out of, or not
join, an occupational scheme. But the guidance leaves issues unclear,
including whether life companies which sell through independent financial
advisers should take on the administration of the questionnaires.
This was discussed at the Association of British Insurers last week but it
has proved impossible to find a consensus. Many companies will not want to
send out the questionnaires before a decision, even though delays will make
the deadlines for dealing with cases where there is the most risk of poor
advice harder to meet.
SIB has said that most of the 350,000 priority cases should be reviewed by
the end of 1996.
</TEXT>
