<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Labour looks at 'windfall' tax on lottery group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party may seek to impose a 'windfall' tax on Camelot, the
consortium which runs the National Lottery.
Some shadow cabinet members believe the terms in the National Lottery
licence under which Camelot will receive 5 per cent of the revenues for the
initial seven years are unjustifiably generous given the lottery's immediate
success.
They are therefore considering a tax on Camelot's share of lottery proceeds
if Labour wins the next general election. They see this as one way to
redress the balance without renegotiating the licence.
Although ticket sales have been strong since the lottery's launch last
month, a reliable picture of Camelot's finances is unlikely to be available
until early next summer, when it is expected to publish its first annual
report.
When Camelot won the licence to run the lottery in March it was believed
that its profit levels would be well under 1 per cent of sales and probably
about 0.6 per cent.
The consortium - whose members include Cadbury Schweppes, the food and
drinks group, ICL, the computer group, and De La Rue, the banknote printer
which this week bought Portals for Pounds 682m - says it will be 'several
years' before it breaks even. The 5 per cent of lottery revenues which
Camelot receives must cover all its costs.
In March the consortium forecast total sales of Pounds 32bn in the seven
years of the licence and payments of Pounds 9bn to good causes such as
charity and the arts. This implies revenue to Camelot of Pounds 1.6bn over
the period.
The consortium says Pounds 100m was invested before the lottery started,
with more to follow as the number of terminals is increased from 10,000 at
present to 40,000 by the end of 1996.
There are plans to introduce a series of scratch card games as part of the
lottery from next spring.
</TEXT>
