<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Five die in air freighter crash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three aircrew and two cargo handlers were killed yesterday morning when
their Air Algerie Boeing 737-200 air freighter, on charter to Phoenix
Aviation, crashed on its approach to Coventry Airport.
The freighter hit an electricity pylon and clipped the roofs of two houses
before catching fire. It came to rest in woodland between the Willenhall
housing estate and the Coventry eastern by-pass.
There were no casualties on the ground. Chief Superintendent Peter Clay of
West Midlands Police said: 'It just missed a housing estate and we have to
be thankful for that.' Electricity supplies to large sections of Coventry
were cut off for several hours.
Phoenix Aviation chartered the aircraft to carry live cattle to France and
the Netherlands. The aircraft, having taken a load to Amsterdam, was
returning empty to Coventry after a diversion to East Midlands Airport
because of fog. Coventry was still misty at the time of the crash.
Department of Transport air accident investigators have started to search
for evidence which will establish why the aircraft prematurely lost
altitude. Police said the flight recorder had been found.
Willenhall residents said they had warned of the dangers of low flying
aircraft for 20 years.
</TEXT>
