<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Railtrack sell-off faces court test
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Employment Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The RMT transport union is to seek leave from the High Court for a judicial
review of last month's government decision to privatise Railtrack, which
maintains the railway track and signal infrastructure.
The challenge follows the recent High Court success by 10 unions, including
the RMT, in overturning the home secretary's attempt to change the forms of
compensation to victims under the Criminal Injuries Compensation Board, and
by this week's climbdown by Mr Michael Portillo, employment secretary, in
accepting a House of Lords judgment that part-time workers should have most
of the employment rights enjoyed by full-time workers.
The union says that powers to privatise Railtrack do not exist in the 1993
legislation that covers the move of the railway industry out of public
ownership, that the government 'deceived' parliament about the immediate
future of Railtrack during the passage of the act, and that the government's
proposals for Railtrack conflict with European Union directives.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, the union's general secretary, said yesterday: 'Following
intensive discussions with our legal advisers we have concluded the
government may be acting outside its powers in privatising Railtrack.
'There are vital constitutional issues here which must be addressed. The
government has a deplorable record of acting outside its powers and I am
confident that, given the chance to argue our case, the court will again
tell the government to think again.'
The union said in a statement it expected its case would be held early in
the new year.
It added that the detailed grounds for the challenge were still being
discussed with its solicitors but that the government was vulnerable.
Warburg mandate, Page 17
