<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / QE2 passengers threaten a sit-in
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Angry passengers on the Queen Elizabeth 2's ill-fated Christmas cruise are
threatening to stage a sit-in on the ship in New York tonight unless
directors of Cunard, the liner's owner, come aboard and offer them immediate
compensation.
Mr Peter Ludlow, travelling on the QE2 on a Pounds 7,500 cruise to the
Caribbean, said that about 150 passengers, due to disembark in New York,
were now planning to stay on the ship.
Mr Ludlow said by telephone from the ship last night: 'They are all prepared
not to come off until board members turn up to see us.'
Passengers have been angered by Cunard's refusal to discuss compensation
with them until they return home. Their luxury cruises have been disrupted
by the QE2's unfinished Pounds 30m refit.
Almost 500 passengers were unable to sail with the ship when it left
Southampton on Saturday because work was still going on in their cabins. A
further 158 UK passengers due to join the cruise in New York had their
holidays cancelled on Tuesday.
Passengers on board have complained of conditions resembling a 'building
site' - overflowing toilets, 'stinking' swimming pools and closed
facilities.
Mr Ludlow said a second group of about 80 passengers was planning to start
legal action in the US through an American lawyer who is herself a
passenger.
Mr Ludlow said: 'It is all getting quite factional here, among the
passengers. It is getting a bit like Bosnia.' Passengers on the
top-of-the-range round the world cruise have formed their own group, but are
unlikely to take any immediate action.
All three groups of passengers yesterday held their own meetings as well as
attending a meeting with Captain Ron Warwick.
Mr Ludlow, who is acting as a spokesman for disgruntled passengers, said he
was concerned about safety. He said that building materials strewn around
the ship were partly blocking some fire escapes.
Meanwhile, an undisclosed number of US passengers due to join the cruise in
New York had their holidays cancelled yesterday. The New York office of
Cunard said that 1,000 passengers would leave New York tonight on the next
leg of the QE2's cruise.
But it admitted that it had been 'adjusting the inventory' - fewer cabins
would be available - and passengers who could not be accommodated would be
offered alternative cruises in compensation.
Observer, Page 15
