<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / World Trade News: Pact curbs shipbuilding subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The world's leading shipbuilding countries yesterday signed a pact to end
the subsidising of large vessels and adopt international trade rules by
January 1 1996.
After five years of negotiation, the industries agreed to eliminate both
direct and indirect subsidies, to create common rules for domestic and
export credit financing of ships, and to establish a strong enforcement
mechanism to discourage violations of rules.
The pact was signed in Paris by Japan, South Korea, Norway, the EU and the
US. It also extends to shipbuilding the protection of anti-dumping regimes,
which US shipbuilders said would raise ship prices to 'more realistic
levels'.
Mr Thomas Jones, chairman of the US shipbuilders council, yesterday
applauded the agreement. 'Foreign governments have been in a subsidy
competition to assist their shipyards to capture market share.' Without the
pact 'this situation would continue and even escalate, thereby perpetuating
the competitive disadvantage of unsubsidised US shipyards. He called on the
Clinton administration to 'actively oppose' the introduction of new
subsidies which would violate the agreement - specifically, subsidies for
French shipyards 'as reported in the press'.
The shipbuilding pact was provisionally agreed in July but opposed by the
French for months.
</TEXT>
