<HEADLINE>
FT  22 DEC 94 / Mexican devaluation hits region's markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TED BARDACKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mexico's stock market fell heavily yesterday and short-term interest rates
rose sharply following Tuesday's 15 per cent devaluation of the peso,
pulling down other Latin American markets.
Analysts said that while the devaluation was probably a good long-term move
for Mexico's economy, there were immediate questions about new President
Ernesto Zedillo's resolve to maintain a conservative monetary and fiscal
policy. There were also worries about the amount of international reserves
available to the central bank to support the peso.
'The government did something it swore it wasn't going to do,' said Mr Felix
Boni of the Mexican brokerage firm Interacciones. 'Investors don't like
surprises, especially ones like this which are difficult to assimilate.' In
London analysts said investors were worried that the government might be
forced to make a second devaluation.
The IPC index, the main stock market indicator, closed down 3.1 per cent,
recovering from its midday fall of 11.63 per cent. At the weekly auction of
government paper, short-term interest rates rose 2.25 percentage points over
last week to 16 per cent and moved as high as 30 per cent in secondary
trading. The peso continued to trade at or near its maximum lower limit of
4.002 pesos to the dollar, settling at 3.997.
In Argentina the Buenos Aires stock market's blue-chip index closed 5.74 per
cent lower in reaction to the Mexican turbulence. In Brazil, shares on the
Sao Paulo exchange fell 6.3 per cent and the central bank intervened
repeatedly in support of the currency.
The Mexican government had cited political instability related to the armed
conflict in the southern state of Chiapas as one of the reasons behind the
devaluation, rather than economic fundamentals. However, the afternoon
recovery of the stock market was spurred by a international conference call
placed to hundreds of foreign investors by Mr Augustin Carstens of Banco de
Mexico, the central bank, and Mr Carlos Mendoza of Nafin, the state-owned
investment bank, who said the devaluation had an economic basis as well, and
the government would seek to raise additional revenues through an aggressive
privatisation programme.
Mr Carstens and Mr Mendoza acknowledged that the devaluation had also been
intended to protect the country's international reserves, reported to have
fallen to Dollars 10bn-Dollars 12bn, from Dollars 24.5bn at the beginning of
the year. Analysts said a continued drop in the market would jeopardise
reserves even further.
Mexico's economic cabinet met Mr Zedillo late into the afternoon to define
additional strategies. The government has at its disposal a Dollars 6bn
credit line set up with the US and Canada in March to maintain currency
stability. Finance Ministry officials denied rumours that the line had been
used, but said that it was one of many options being discussed with the
president.
World stock markets, Page 33;
Editorial Comment and Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>MXZ  Mexico.
    ARZ  Argentina, South America.
</CN>
