<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / International Capital Markets: Battle looms for North
American gold producers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A battle is looming between two North American gold producers,
Vancouver-based Granges and Atlas Corporation, which has its headquarters in
Denver.
Atlas acquired 37.2 per cent of Granges for CDollars 50.7m (USDollars 36.9m)
from MIM, the Australian resources group. Mr Steve Manz, Atlas president,
said recently he had the support of enough other Granges shareholders to
take control of that company's board at the next annual meeting - which must
be held before June next year.
The objective, said Mr Manz, was a full merger of Atlas, Granges and a third
company, Hycroft, in which Granges has a 50 per cent stake. This would
create a group with an annual output in 1996 of at least 150,000 troy ounces
of gold.
Mr John Auston, president of Granges, said these comments suggested that
Atlas was ready to breach a formal agreement signed at the time of the
purchase of the MIM holding.
Atlas agreed that the number of its appointees to the Granges board would be
in proportion to its shareholding. Atlas also agreed not to take its holding
in Granges to more than 40 per cent without making an offer to all Granges
shareholders.
Mr Manz denied there had been any improper soliciting of proxies by Atlas.
'We were approached by Granges shareholders,' he insisted. As for the
standstill agreement, 'we'll let time take care of that,' he declared.
</TEXT>
