<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / International Bonds: Two borrowers brave subdued conditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Christmas slowdown in the eurobond market continued yesterday, with only
two borrowers braving the subdued market conditions with highly structured
deals.
SMM, a special purpose vehicle backed by debt and equity assets, launched a
five-tranche multi-currency offering via J. P. Morgan.
The issue, which included fixed-rate and floating-rate dollar tranches and
sterling, D-Mark and Swiss franc floating-rate tranches, was targeted at
specific investor groups, a syndicate official at J. P. Morgan said.
The offering met with interest from institutional accounts, with a number of
large block purchases in continental Europe, he said.
The main Dollars 719m tranche of two-year floating-rate notes offered a
coupon of 12 1/2 basis points over three-month Libor.
Nippon Credit launched a Dollars 150m issue of five-year credit enhanced
performance bonds for a separate special purpose vehicle. The offering found
demand from institutional investors worldwide, Nippon Credit said.
The Canadian province of Alberta has established a Dollars 1.5bn medium term
note programme, Merrill Lynch, which arranged the deal, said in a statement.
The programme will allow for the distribution of notes into the US, the
euromarkets and the Canadian market. The notes can be denominated in a
variety of currencies with a maturity of up to 15-years, Merrill Lynch said.
In a similar move, Credit Suisse announced a Dollars 1.5bn multi-currency
medium-term note programme.
Elsewhere, the devaluation of the Mexican peso had little impact on spreads
on Mexican eurobonds, analysts said. The effect on confidence was greater in
the more liquid Brady bond market where bond prices fell by about  3/4 point
before recovering slightly.
Unibanco Leasing launched a Dollars 50m issue of three-year FRNs offering
330 basis points over six-month Libor.
</TEXT>
