<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / International Company News: TSB sells Irish bank's loan book
for IPounds 116m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TSB Group, the UK's sixth largest bank, has closed its Irish operations with
the sale of the loan book of its Irish Business Bank subsidiary to Anglo
Irish Bank for IPounds 116m (Pounds 114.6m).
Anglo Irish said the sum represented the net book value; the gross value was
IPounds 140m, the difference being the provision for bad and doubtful debts.
Mr Peter Killen, Anglo Irish's executive director responsible for risk
assets, said the new loan book, comprising about 400 accounts in the
medium-sized corporate and professional market, reflected the spread of the
existing specialised areas of business and would take its risk assets above
IPounds 1bn.
Three years ago, Anglo Irish entered talks about buying Hill Samuel
(Ireland), as Irish Business Bank was formerly known. Negotiations broke
down the following April after completion of the due diligence process left
the two sides unable to agree on a price.
The deal announced yesterday, which is subject to regulatory approval, would
be fully funded from Anglo Irish's own resources, Mr Killen said.
The TSB subsidiary had virtually stopped new lending during the last couple
of years and the emphasis had been on structuring the operation in a form
that would attract buyers. A total of 37 jobs will be lost.
The disposal marks the end of a process of withdrawal by TSB from Ireland
over the last few years as the group moves to concentrate on its UK
business.
In April this year it sold the Hill Samuel Fagan Investment Management
business to Allied Irish Banks for an undisclosed amount. In 1992, UDT Bank,
part of Hill Samuel Ireland, was sold to Woodchester Investments, the
Dublin-based leasing and financial services group, for IPounds 23.4m cash.
</TEXT>
