<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Regulator's hint led to Trafalgar Pounds 20 rebate offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By:BY CHRIS TIGHE and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trafalgar House, the conglom-erate mounting a hostile bid for Northern
Electric, decided to offer a Pounds 20 rebate to each of its 1.3m customers
at the prompting of Prof Stephen Littlechild, electricity industry
regulator.
Mr Brian Keelan, of Swiss Bank Corporation, advising Trafalgar, disclosed
yesterday that the rebate concept arose from a meeting about a month ago at
the regulator's office.
Mr Keelan said: 'Prof Littlechild made it clear it would be easier for him
to consider a bid for a regional electricity company that contained in its
terms a tangible benefit for the consumer, over and above the tariff
reduction that was published in August.
He added: 'Prof Littlechild decided he was Robin Hood. To walk us through
Sherwood Forest, the consumer would have to have something tangible, not a
statement of intentions or a warm and fuzzy feeling.'
Describing this as a 'hint', Mr Keelan said: 'We would probably have done
something like that anyway, but it's helpful to be guided by the regulator.'
Mr Keelan's comments, made at a press conference in Newcastle upon Tyne,
where Northern is based, will strengthen claims by Prof Littlechild's
critics that the regulatory regime, to take effect from April, is too lax.
'If Prof Littlechild believes Northern can afford to hand over Pounds 26m to
customers under a new management, why did he not ask the existing regime to
do it in August?' one analyst asked.
Shares in Northern and most other regional electricity companies fell
yesterday after Prof Littlechild published a consultation paper on
Trafalgar's bid. Although he reaches no firm conclusions in the paper, he
discusses the possibility of a referral of the bid to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission.
If Trafalgar were to take over Northern, he says, it would be the first time
a public electricity supply licence would be held by a subsidiary company
rather than its parent.
Prof Littlechild's initial view is that this is insufficient reason to bar a
takeover but he wants to consider licence changes in the event of takeovers.
He points to concerns about the resources a parent may provide to its
electricity subsidiary 'to enable it to undertake its functions' and says he
will be considering licence changes to take these into account.
</TEXT>
