<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Mexico devalues the peso amid deepening unrest in Chiapas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TED BARDACKE and STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mexico's new government yesterday allowed a big devaluation of the peso in
the face of mounting outflows of capital, reversing a long-held policy
permitting only a gradual depreciation of the currency.
It is the first significant devaluation by Mexico since 1987. The move by
the government of President Ernesto Zedillo, who assumed office on December
1, followed 10 months of capital outflows from the country, which
intensified again over the past couple of weeks.
Government officials said they expected the peso would float upwards in
value early next year, as political tensions in the country began to ease.
Sales of Mexican assets by foreign investors reflected worries about
deepening political tensions in the southern state of Chiapas, analysts
said. Investors also had concerns about the size of the country's current
account deficit, which will amount to some Dollars 28bn (Pounds 18bn) this
year.
Armed rebels mounted an offensive in Chiapas in January, demanding more
rights for indigenous peoples and enhanced democracy. A tense impasse with
the military has continued and this week some rebels occupied the Chiapas
town of Simojovel and blocked roads around it. Several hundred government
troops, backed by two light tanks, were reported last night to be heading
for the town.
The peso closed yesterday at 3.996 to the dollar, 15 per cent down on
Monday's close. This follows a depreciation of some 10 per cent earlier in
the year.
The government announced that the permitted floor value of the peso would
drop to 4.0016 to the US dollar, compared with Monday's floor of 3.466. The
permitted daily slide, which amounts to some 4 per cent a year, will be
allowed to continue.
The Mexican stock market reacted favourably to the move, rising almost 6 per
cent in heavy trading before falling back to close 1.97 per cent up
following Monday's 4.2 per cent fall.
Mr Jaime Serra Puche, finance minister, said political pressure was the main
reason behind the devaluation. Analysts said a seasonal demand for dollars
by private companies, a switch by domestic investors from peso-denominated
government paper to dollar-denominated securities and a general pull-out of
Mexican stocks by foreign investors were also factors in the devaluation.
Nerves over deficit, Page 5
