FT  21 DEC 94 / People: New chief executive for BACC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM HALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For the first time in 75 years, the British-American Chamber of Commerce
(BACC) is to be run by an American. Daniel Bayer, below, a New York city
official, has been appointed chief executive of the BACC's operations in
London and New York.
Bayer, 46, a former Fulbright scholar who has a doctorate in mathematical
logic and philosophy from Rockefeller University, takes over from Peter
Felix. The BACC was set up to foster Anglo-US trade and investment; the job
of chief executive has traditionally been held by a British national based
in New York. However, the organisation has become increasingly involved in
two-way trade and investment between the US and Britain.
Bayer has been vice-president for economic development of the New York
Chamber of Commerce and Industry and its affiliate the New York City
partnership.
