<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Farm wages board granted reprieve
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday bowed to pressure from farmers and their employees
and said it would keep the Agricultural Wages Board, the country's last
remaining statutory minimum pay body.
The decision, believed to have been won by Mr William Waldegrave,
agriculture minister, in the face of opposition from more hardline
ministers, was warmly welcomed by both sides of the industry.
They had feared that the board, which sets minimum pay, holidays, sick pay
and overtime rates for 180,000 farmworkers in England and Wales, would
suffer the same fate as the wages councils which were abolished last year.
Mr Waldegrave said: 'It is clear from the responses to consultation that
there is wide acceptance, from both sides of the agricultural industry, of
the present arrangements.' Out of 4,000 responses to the Ministry of
Agriculture only 10 advocated abolition.
The TGWU general union, which represents farmworkers, welcomed what it
called 'an absolute victory', saying the government had decided not to risk
legislation that could run into opposition from rural Conservative MPs. Mr
Barrie Leathwood, national secretary of the rural and agricultural workers'
section, said countryside interests had played an important part in two
other government retreats this year - on privatisation of the Forestry
Commission and the Post Office.
Mr Leathwood said: 'Mr Waldegrave is a farmer himself and understands how
the industry operates. He will have used the argument about the impact (of
abolition) on rural areas and rural earnings.'
Mr Gavin Strang, Labour agriculture spokesman, has campaigned strongly
against abolition and described the government's decision as 'a truly
welcome U-turn'. He said a report by the London School of Economics had
shown that minimum wages had not reduced agricultural employment.
The National Farmers' Union said the board was central to good industrial
relations and to establishing an effective career structure for workers.
Farmworkers, whose pay body has been under review for 18 months, have had a
relatively good year. They won an above average pay rise of 4.9 per cent in
the summer, and the extension of full-time workers' rights to 38,000
part-timers from next month.
Mr Waldegrave said the board would continue to be kept 'under close review'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
