<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / BBC in US deal for news service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC plans to launch its 24-hour satellite news service, BBC World, in
the US in February in a deal with International News Network (INN) of New
York.
The launch, much earlier than expected and less than a month after BBC World
goes on air in Europe, is designed to take advantage of changes in US cable
regulations.
The Federal Communications Commission recently decided that cable operators
could charge more for their basic cable packages if new channels were
offered.
Mr Reese Schonfeld, the former president and chief executive of the CNN
network, who is chairman of INN, said yesterday that he expected a high
proportion of big cable operators to at least test BBC World in their
markets.
He conceded, however, that competition would be intense with more than 60
channels competing for about six additional slots.
Mr Schonfeld said CNN provided the who, what, where and when of television
news. 'BBC World will add the how and the why with the help of pieces from
Newsnight and Panorama,' he added.
</TEXT>
