<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Breaches of rules emerge as Lautro imposes fines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Serious breaches of regulatory rules emerged yesterday with the announcement
of fines imposed by Lautro, the life insurance watchdog, on two friendly
societies - Homeowners and Ideal Benefit.
Homeowners, which has about 250,000 members, was fined Pounds 125,000 and
must pay the regulator's costs of Pounds 30,000 after admitting nine charges
relating primarily to misleading advertisements over a period of more than
two years.
Ideal Benefit, which has only 23,000 members, was fined Pounds 25,000 and
told to pay costs of Pounds 6,000 after admitting that for almost four years
from April 1990 it had not had effective procedures in place to ensure it
met regulatory standards.
The charges against Homeowners were mainly about advertisements in
newspapers and through direct mail for single premium investments -
particularly growth bonds.
Lautro, which has been superseded by the Personal Investment Authority, also
criticised the society for 'frequent and inordinate delay in making any
satisfactory response'.
Mr Roger Hocking, Homeowners' commercial director, said that following
Lautro's visits earlier this year and the subsequent inquiry, the society's
compliance manager had left by mutual agreement.
Homeowners has appointed an assistant compliance officer and is in the
process of recruiting a senior compliance manager.
Lautro did not find any sign that investors had suffered but the society is
writing to all the 17,000 members affected and has set up a helpline for
them.
The charges against Ideal Benefit related to faults uncovered in the second
round of routine inspection visits by the regulator, which was carried out
in March this year.
They include not taking up references for people appointed as sales agents,
poor record-keeping, and not sending full information to people who
complained.
</TEXT>
