<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Court raps government over night flights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Transport was yesterday forced to reconsider its current
controls on night flights into Heathrow and two other airports after the
High Court ruled that the manner of their introduction had been illegal.
A judge ruled that Mr John MacGregor, the former transport secretary, had
acted unlawfully in failing to provide proper public consultation over the
latest controls on night-time take-offs and landings at Heathrow, Gatwick
and Stansted.
The judge said a consultation paper issued by the Department of Transport in
January last year was misleading because it did not make clear that the new
arrangements would mean an increase in noise levels at Heathrow.
The ruling was welcomed by the local authorities which brought the court
action against the department. Mr Richard Buxton, the authorities'
solicitor, said the ruling would force the government to reconsider its
current quota system for night flights.
'Seldom is a government department found by the courts to have misled so
many people over such an important environmental issue. The government
essentially has to go back to square one,' he said.
The department was given leave to appeal over the ruling. A spokesman said
the judgment would be studied carefully before a decision was taken over the
appropriate response. However, he said the controls would remain in place
until March 26 next year.
Although ministers were yesterday digesting the detail of the judgment,
officials conceded that a fresh round of consultations was now inevitable.
The consultation paper published in last year stated that under the proposed
controls noise levels would not exceed those for summer 1988.
However, this ignored the fact that the actual noise levels for 1988 were
two-thirds of levels allowed for in theory under controls in place at the
time.
Mr Justice Latham said: 'I do not consider that consultation based upon a
document which can mislead in this way can be described as full and fair
consultation in the sense that (local authorities) could legitimately
expect.'
The controls phased in this winter are based on a mixture of a quota system
intended to encourage greater use of quieter aeroplanes and a ceiling on the
number of individual flights. It was intended these controls would apply
until summer 1998.
The successful legal challenge was brought by the borough councils of
Windsor and Maidenhead, Hounslow, Hillingdon, Richmond and Slough, and
Surrey County Council.
The department is expected to draw up new night flight regulations to cover
next summer's flights.
</TEXT>
