<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Cunard blames QE2 delay on contractors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cunard, the cruise operator, yesterday blamed subcontractors for the delayed
completion of a Pounds 30m refit of the liner Queen Elizabeth 2, which
resulted in 500 passengers being turned away from its Christmas cruise.
The company said the refit, which involved the refurbishment of all 960
cabins and the building of many facilities in 30 days, was 'the biggest ever
undertaken in such a short time'. But Cunard denied being over-ambitious.
It said: 'All the contractors knew what we were undertaking and were
prepared to tender for it. They convinced us they could finish on time and
that was why they got the contracts.'
Cunard emphasised that of more than 50 contractors, only 'about three'
British companies - which it refused to name - had not finished on time.
About 57 per cent of refitting work by value went to British companies, the
rest to German and other international groups.
Passengers have complained that the liner resembled a 'building site', with
plumbing not functioning in many cabins and equipment strewn across public
areas.
Captain Ron Warwick of the QE2 told Cunard yesterday, however, that more
cabins were constantly being opened, allowing passengers to move into better
accommodation.
The main refit contract, involving structural work inside the ship, was
awarded to Blohm &amp; Voss, the Hamburg-based shipbuilder. It said it had
completed the work on time but cabin work had been subcontracted to UK
companies by Cunard.
Cunard said it received assurances from subcontractors that the refit would
be finished on time. But it became apparent on Friday that insufficient
cabins would be ready for Saturday's departure.
Subcontractors yesterday refused to comment on specific causes of the delay.
Trimline, the Hampshire-based company named as one of the companies which
was late, confirmed it was talking to Cunard about the contract.
A company executive said he was 'extremely brassed off' at suggestions that
the company had been at fault. Trimline had been refitting more than 700
bathrooms on the QE2 and started work in July. He said: 'We were never
running late, and are confident the work will be finished on time, hopefully
by the time the ship reaches New York.'
He said Trimline depended on other companies finishing their work before it
could refit the bathrooms, and 'unforeseen events' over which Trimline had
no control were to blame for the delay.
One shipbuilding industry official said the timetable for the refit was
'very, very tight'.
</TEXT>
