<DATE>941221
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Banking regulator urged for societies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The regulation of building societies should be amalgamated into banking
supervision instead of being left to a separate body, a Commons committee
recommended yesterday.
A report from the Treasury committee of MPs said that the Building Societies
Commission could be absorbed into the supervisory division of the Bank of
England.
It called for building societies to be able to undertake a broader range of
activities, limited only by what their members decided and what their
supervisor said was prudent, but also to be more accountable to their
members.
The committee argued that the case for a single regulator grew stronger as
societies diversified more widely into financial services.
It said: 'There may be a point at which the expanding activities of the
larger societies will require the supervisory disciplines of Bank of England
scrutiny.'
The MPs also highlighted advantages in changing the law to allow societies
to become banks while retaining their mutual status.
They said the government should consult the Bank of England about developing
this option as an alternative route for societies that wanted wider powers.
The report has been timed to be taken into account by the Treasury's own
review of societies' powers and accountability, which is expected to be
published in mid-January.
As mutual organisations, societies are owned by their millions of members
rather than by a separate category of shareholders. The MPs criticised
societies, saying there was evidence they had 'tended to take their members
for granted', and put forward some specific changes to improve involvement
and accountability.
The report dismissed the arguments advanced by societies against paying
dividends or loyalty bonuses, and said the organisations should be compelled
to be more open with members about accumulated reserves, and should consider
the scope for such payments.
It called for greater use of postal voting and for further work on making it
easier for members to nominate directors. The idea of mutuality was 'under
strain from the transformation of regional deposit-taking and
mortgage-lending bodies into national multi-faceted financial
organisations'.
The committee's backing for a more permissive legislative regime and ways of
making societies more accountable to members - such as by distributing
'user-friendly' leaflets about membership rights to all members - is in line
with thinking in the Treasury review.
However, if societies are to be given wider powers anyway, the government is
much less likely to favour creating a class of mutual banks.
Halifax Building Society, the UK's largest, advocated this idea, but has
since announced plans to become a public limited company with a full banking
licence after merging with Leeds Permanent Building Society.
</TEXT>
